[Patient] How much water should I drink each day for my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for about 1.5-2 liters of fluid per day, including water and other liquids.
[Patient] Can I drink juice or soda instead of water?
[Educator] It's best to stick to water or unsweetened drinks to avoid extra sugar and sodium.
[Patient] How do I know if I'm drinking too much fluid?
[Educator] Watch for weight gain, swelling in your legs, or increased shortness of breath.
[Patient] What if I feel thirsty all the time?
[Educator] Sip water throughout the day but be mindful of your total fluid intake.
[Patient] Can I have salty snacks if I'm thirsty?
[Educator] Try to choose low-sodium snacks like unsalted nuts or fresh fruits instead.
[Patient] How can I track my fluid intake?
[Educator] Keep a log of how much you drink each day to help monitor your intake.
[Patient] What should I do if I notice sudden weight gain?
[Educator] Contact your healthcare team immediately as it could indicate fluid retention.
[Patient] Are there any foods I should avoid for my heart failure?
[Educator] Limit high-sodium foods like processed meats, canned soups, and fast food.
[Patient] Can I have soup if it's low-sodium?
[Educator] Yes, opt for homemade or low-sodium canned soups to control your sodium intake.
[Patient] How can I afford low-sodium foods on a tight budget?
[Educator] Look for sales, use coupons, and consider visiting food banks for assistance.
[Patient] What if I can't afford my heart failure medications?
[Educator] Ask about prescription assistance programs or discuss generic options with your doctor.
[Patient] How often should I check my weight to monitor fluid retention?
[Educator] Weigh yourself at the same time each day, ideally in the morning before eating. 
[Patient] Thank you for the advice. I will work on managing my fluid intake better.
[Educator] You're welcome. Remember, small changes can make a big difference in managing your heart failure.